name: Rhys Stanley
bio: The Cats’ big man reached second spot in Geelong’s all time hit-out list in 2023, and is set to reach his 200 game milestone this year. Battling injury throughout 2023, he played just 13 games after a fractured eye socket sidelined him from rounds six to twelve. Stanley will line up for his 10th season with the Cats, while also being touted as a strong mentor for emerging ruckman Toby Conway.

name: Zach Tuohy
bio: Created a slice of AFL history last year when he broke Melbourne great Jim Stynes’ record for the most games by an Irish player, after making his 265th appearance in round 17. Tuohy continued to be a reliable asset for the Cats in 2023, playing 20 games while continuing to display his elite foot skills across half back.

name: Brandan Parfitt
bio: The tough inside midfielder battled injury and illness at times last year, but showed his class in the final game of the year amassing 26 disposals and eight clearances against the Western Bulldogs. Was consistently amongst the leading disposal winners each week in the VFL, while continuing to develop his game. Will be looking forward to a more consistent run in 2024.

name: Tanner Bruhn
bio: One of the highlights of the Cats 2023 season was the development of Bruhn, who played 19 games for the year averaging over 16 disposals and five tackles per game. Had a career high 12 tackles in the round 12 win over the Bulldogs, and an equal career high seven clearances against Collingwood in round 22. Pushed forward to kick important goals throughout the season, and will be one of the key figures leading the Cat's next generation.

name: Jeremy Cameron
bio: The star forward dominated the opening half of the 2023 season, kicking 33 goals in his first eight rounds including six majors against Carlton and seven against Hawthorn. Carrying a shoulder injury in the back half of the season, Cameron remained dangerous up forward which was highlighted in his seven goal performance against Collingwood in round 22. Finished the season with 53 goals from 20 games, and will again enter the 2024 campaign as one of the competition’s top forwards.

name: Toby Conway
bio: One of the most exciting prospects heading into 2024 is a fit and firing Toby Conway, who fought his way back from injury to make his AFL debut in the final round of the 2023 season. Gained plenty of attention in his first game at the top level, taking it right up to Bulldogs star Tim English for much of the night. Looked a class above at VFL level after returning from injury midway through the season, and will look to find a more consistent run this year.

name: Shaun Mannagh
bio: The mature age recruit joins the Cats from Werribee, landing on the radar of numerous clubs after a six goal performance in the 2023 VFL Grand Final. The 26 year old amassed 28 disposals in the Grand Final and won the Norm Goss Medal as best afield, despite playing in the losing side. Mannagh also spent three years in Richmond’s VFL program, with Geelong selecting him early in the second round of the AFL draft.

name: Jake Kolodjashnij
bio: Kolodjashnij has been a consistent and durable defender for the Cats, and will enter his 10th AFL season in 2024. The defender kept opposition forwards in check across his 19 appearances last year, with his ability to play tall or small invaluable to the Geelong defensive unit. Took a career high 11 marks in the round eight win over Adelaide.

name: Max Holmes
bio: With an abundance of speed and class, Holmes continues to develop into a dual threat with the ability to play as a midfielder or off of half back for the Cats. Pieced together a strong campaign last year averaging 19 disposals a game, while doubling his total tackles from 42 in 2022 to 88 in 2023. Racked up a career high 33 disposals in the round 18 win over Essendon, and will be a crucial piece to the Geelong puzzle once again this season.

name: Mitchell Knevitt
bio: Showed plenty of potential in his second season with the Cats, playing eight matches at the top level while continuing to develop his game at VFL level in between. Knevitt produced career high numbers in disposals (17), tackles (seven) and inside 50’s (five) in Geelong’s round 12 win over the Bulldogs. Likened to versatile Cat Mark Blicavs, Knevitt showed that with his height and agility he can be a real asset for Geelong heading into the 2024 season.

name: Mitchell Edwards
bio: An exciting young ruckman from Western Australia that possesses plenty of talent, with height and a natural leap that gives him a distinct advantage at stoppages. Recorded strong numbers at the Draft Combine, which lead to the Cats selecting him early in the second round. Edwards has incredible mobility for a player of his size, and will be one to watch as he begins his AFL journey in 2024.

name: Jack Bowes
bio: Joined the Cats via trade at the end of 2022 and put together a solid debut season at GMHBA Stadium, playing 17 games in a number of different roles from half back to half forward. Averaged over 15 disposals per game in 2023 while learning a new system, including a 25 possession and one goal performance against North Melbourne in round 17.

name: Jhye Clark
bio: The highly touted youngster showed plenty of his potential in the opening half of the season, earning his AFL debut in round nine as the tactical substitute against Richmond. Looked comfortable at the top level before injury brought his season to an abrupt end the following week. Averaged 16 disposals and three tackles in his first six games at VFL level, with Geelong’s highest pick since 2007 set to develop further with a more consistent run in 2024.

name: Connor O'Sullivan
bio: The Cat's first pick from last year’s draft, the athletic tall defender was a standout for the Allies at the 2023 AFL National Under-18 Championships, winning their MVP award and All-Australian honours. Averaged 18 disposals at 86% efficiency, while also plucking eight marks per game and providing great rebounding off half back. Possesses an exciting natural leap, good speed, and elite endurance.

name: George Stevens
bio: A tough inside midfielder who thrives in contested football situations, Stevens impressed in his junior career as a clearance specialist for the GWS Rebels. Played two games for the Geelong VFL team in 2023, amassing 29 disposals against Collingwood late in the season. Captained the Australian under-18 team against SANFL and VFL sides, and won All-Australian honours at the AFL National Under-18 Championships. Stevens was named captain of the Coates Talent League Team of the Year, after averaging 29 disposals and five tackles.

name: Sam De Koning
bio: One of the AFL’s brightest prospects and the rising star of the Geelong defensive unit, De Koning will once again be the Cat's anchor on the last line of defence with his intercept and contested marking prowess. Set to reach his 50 game milestone early in 2024, De Koning will benefit from a more consistent Geelong lineup in 2024 after being thrown into the ruck at times last year. Took some big hits at the start of the season, but continued to impress in 2023 as he quickly approaches the top echelon of defenders right across the competition.

name: Lawson Humphries
bio: A 182cm wingman from Swan Districts with elite ball use and decision making, Humphries developed into a weapon in the WAFL last year splitting his time between seniors and reserves. Ultimately starred in the Swan Districts reserves premiership, displaying his elite skills on both sides of his body. Geelong selected Humphries in the fifth round of the AFL draft.

name: Tyson Stengle
bio: Stengle put together another solid campaign in 2023 booting goals in 15 of his last 16 games, despite suffering a nasty injury to his arm early in the season. Kicked a career high five goals in the round 17 win over North Melbourne and three against Essendon the following week, finishing with 27 majors for the season as Geelong’s premier small forward. Another Cat who would benefit from an injury free run this year, Stengle showed his potential in 2022 becoming a Premiership player and an All-Australian in his debut season with Geelong.

name: Phoenix Foster
bio: Foster showed plenty of potential in a development year at VFL level, spending time at full forward and full back during his first season at Geelong. Averaged 11 disposals and four tackles per game, including a season high 18 disposal game against Sydney early in the season. Has strong contested marking abilities and is an accurate set shot in front of goal.

name: James Willis
bio: Willis played predominantly through the midfield at VFL level in 2023, but a frustrating run with injuries interrupted his campaign. Taken with pick 32 in the 2021 AFL draft, Willis has shown plenty of speed and power when he takes the field with promising signs heading into 2024. His standout performance last year came in round seven against Southport, where he collected 21 disposals and booted three goals.

name: Oliver Wiltshire
bio: The local talent was selected by the Cats late in the AFL draft, following a dominant season with Barwon Heads in the Bellarine Football League. Booted 51 goals in 2023 including a bag of 12 against Modewarre early in the season. Had a stint with the Geelong Falcons in 2021 and holds plenty of speed, great endurance, and brilliant skills on both sides of his body.

name: Gary Rohan
bio: Set to reach a pair of milestones in 2024, with 200 AFL games and 100 games for the Geelong Football Club well within reach. His best performance last year came in the round 15 win over Melbourne, where Rohan collected 16 disposals, seven marks, four tackles and kicked three crucial goals. The speedy forward is crucial for Geelong in a number of different areas, including his general pressure inside forward 50.

name: Jed Bews
bio: Played 15 games in 2023 after battling various injuries, with his importance to the Geelong defensive unit particularly noted during his absences. The lockdown defender continues to get the toughest tasks against the best small forwards in the competition, and will once again be an important part of the defensive unit in 2024.

name: Tom Hawkins
bio: The star forward is set to break a number of records in 2024, with his 350th game and the Cats all time games record well within reach, while also looking likely to surpass 800 career goals. Hawkins is set for his 18th season with the Cats, and has shown no signs of slowing down after booting a career high eight goals in the round seven win over Essendon last year. The big Cat eclipsed 45 goals in a season for the 13th time in his career, hitting the scoreboard in 18 of his 20 games for the year.

name: Ollie Dempsey
bio: Was rewarded for a strong season in the VFL with five games at the top level, in just his second year at Geelong. The standout performance came in the final game of the season where Dempsey collected 15 disposals, eight tackles and booted a goal against the Bulldogs. Was selected to the VFL Team of the Year despite playing just 14 games, kicking 18 goals, and averaging over 21 disposals.

name: Cameron Guthrie
bio: Battled a toe injury for the opening six weeks of the 2023 season but still proved his importance, averaging over 22 disposals and five tackles per game. Guthrie’s season at AFL level came to an abrupt end after the round six win over Sydney, opting for surgery before returning for one game in the VFL in their final match of the year. As a two-time Carji Greeves Medallist, Guthrie’s importance to the Geelong midfield was truly recognised during his absence, and he will be a big addition back into the lineup in 2024.

name: Tom Atkins
bio: Atkins’ progression from a defensive role player to a midfield star continued in 2023, averaging over 19 disposals and eight tackles per game. He recorded several personal bests throughout the year including 34 disposals against Collingwood in round 22, and nine clearances against Essendon in round 18. Ranked third in the competition for total tackles, on his way to finishing second in the Cats best and fairest while also reaching 100 career games. One of only three Cats to play every game in 2023, while continuing to impress with his leadership both on and off the field.

name: Oscar Murdoch
bio: The versatile defender showed his ability to play tall or small in 2023, while also displaying his elite foot skills and strong intercept marking prowess. Murdoch caught the eye of interested onlookers in the VFL last year, and will look to continue his development in 2024.

name: Gryan Miers
bio: One of the main positives out of the Cats 2023 season was the progression of Gryan Miers, who broke the all time goal assists record with 41 for the home and away season. Finished third in the best and fairest and was one of just three Cats to play all 23 games, averaging over 19 disposals and four inside 50 entries per game. Following his career best season in 2023, Miers will again be a critical piece in Geelong’s forward half this year.

name: Shannon Neale
bio: Earned a recall to the AFL side for the final three games of the season, after averaging 12 disposals and booting 17 goals from eight games in the VFL last year. Showed strong form throughout the year despite battling injuries at different stages, before showing his potential at the top level to close out the year. Demontrated his versatility both as a forward and in the ruck at times, making Neale one to watch for the Cats heading into 2024.

name: Oisin Mullin
bio: Certainly didn’t look out of place in his first season of Australian Rules Football, after crossing over from Ireland has a highly touted Gaelic Football star. Continued to develop across the season and was rewarded with six games at AFL level, racking up 15 disposals on debut against GWS in round 11. Showed great potential with his speed and agility, and will only get better as he continues to get familiar with the oval shaped football.

name: Patrick Dangerfield (C)
bio: Put together a number of big performances in his first season as captain, averaging over 20 disposals and six clearances while also hitting the scoreboard in 10 different games. Most notably amassed 26 disposals, 11 inside 50’s and nine clearances in the round 22 clash with Collingwood. Dangerfield’s hard running and powerful contested work were on full display throughout 2023, but the star midfielder only managed 18 games as he battled injuries at different points of the year. The dynamic Dangerfield will once again be a crucial factor in the Geelong midfield heading into 2024.

name: Oliver Henry
bio: Another big positive to come from the Cats 2023 campaign was the development of Ollie Henry, in his first season at the club after crossing over from Collingwood at the end of 2022. Booted 41 goals from 22 games while kicking four goals on three different occasions, perfectly complementing key forwards Jeremy Cameron and Tom Hawkins. Achieved career high disposals, marks, and tackles at different points of the season.

name: Joe Furphy
bio: Furphy joined the Cats late in 2023 as a Category B rookie, a highly touted junior footballer who initially chose to pursue a professional basketball career. The athletic big man played one game for the Northern Knights in 2018 before opting to pursue his basketball dream. Described as a raw talent with very exciting attributes, including a big leap.

name: Jack Henry
bio: Found some consistency through the middle of the year, managing 11 games after missing the opening nine weeks of the 2023 season through injury. Returned in round 10 and started forward, booting two goals against Fremantle to show his importance to the side as a versatile swingman. Looked rock solid on return to defence, before injury cut his year short in round 21. The Cats will benefit greatly from a fit and firing Henry in 2024.

name: Zach Guthrie
bio: A fourth place finish in the best and fairest for one of the Cats most consistent contributors in 2023, Guthrie took big strides last year and continues to thrive at the top level. Was one of just three players to feature in all 23 games last year, averaging a career high 16 disposals and six marks per game. The highlight was his 26 disposal performance against Port Adelaide in round 14. Showed the ability to play tall or small in defence, ranking second at the club for intercept possessions.

name: Ted Clohesy
bio: Impressed at VFL level for much of the year, before earning his AFL debut in the final round of the season as the tactical substitute against the Western Bulldogs. The tough small forward averaged over 16 disposals and five tackles per game in the VFL, kicking 13 goals from his 18 matches. Started to spend time through the midfield in the back half of the season, adding another element to his game ahead of the 2024 season.

name: Mitch Hardie
bio: Joined the Cats in the 2023 Mid-Season Rookie Draft and impressed right away, collecting 21 disposals and eight tackles in his VFL debut against Frankston. Was drafted from Woodville-West Torrens in the SANFL, after averaging 26 disposals and six clearances per game at the start of the 2023 season. Played mostly as an inside midfielder in the VFL, but also looked comfortable as he spent time across half forward and half back.

name: Mark O'Connor
bio: O’Connor has quickly developed into a valuable and important member of the Geelong line up, with his versatility meaning he can play a number of different roles right across the ground. Averaged over 14 disposals from his 22 games last year, with his dash and rebounding prowess a feature for the Cats off half back. Has shown that he can go into the midfield and perform effective run-with roles, with tackling pressure another strength of the Irishman’s game.

name: Emerson Jeka
bio: Picked up by the Cats in last year’s Rookie Draft as a versatile tall, capable of playing as a key defender with the ability to swing forward. Played a handful of senior games across four seasons at Hawthorn, but battled injury during his time with the club. Played permanently as a forward in his first two VFL seasons, booting 35 goals from his first 15 games before finding a new home down back.

name: Tom Stewart  (V)
bio: The vice captain won his second Carji Greeves Medal and fifth All-Australian jacket in 2023, further cementing his status as one of the games top defenders. Ranked top 10 in the AFL for total rebound 50’s, marks, meters gained, kicks and intercepts. Averaged over 23 disposals, eight marks and eight intercepts per game in 2023 while racking up 20 or more disposals on 17 different occasions. Has now been named to five of the last six All-Australian teams, continuing to build an imposing legacy in the blue and white hoops.

name: Brad Close
bio: Continues to grow as a player each and every year, with 2023 no exception as Close recorded several career highs last year. Amassed 24 disposals in the round 15 win over Melbourne, seven inside 50’s against North Melbourne in round 17, and four goals against West Coast in round five. Was voted best on ground against West Coast and received his first career Brownlow votes, continuing to be an asset with his forward half pressure while booting 21 goals for the season.

name: Mark Blicavs
bio: Put together another solid campaign in 2023 and was closing in on his 250 game milestone, before an injury in the round 20 clash with Fremantle cut his season short. Continues to be one the competition’s most versatile players, with Blicavs’ aerobic capacity meaning he can play right across the ground. Averaged 16 disposals and a career high four clearances per game, while also pushing forward to kick 12 goals from his 19 appearances. Spends valuable time as the back up ruckman, and will be crucial to the Cats once again in 2024.
